Loading Llama 2 from Huggingface

8 steps

In this quest, you will learn how to utilize the Hugging Face platform to implement Large Language Models (LLMs) for various natural language processing (NLP) tasks. You will be guided through setting up your environment, loading pre-trained models, and performing basic operations with Hugging Face Transformers. Additionally, you will explore sentiment analysis using pre-trained models, preparing you for more advanced applications.

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the quest-helpdesk channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.
Join us on Discord

Learning Outcomes

By the end of this quest, you will be able to:
Learn how to install and configure the necessary libraries and tools to work with Hugging Face Transformers.

  • Learn how to access and load pre-trained LLMs from the Hugging Face model hub.
  • Understand how to use pre-trained models to perform basic NLP tasks such as text generation.
  • Gain practical skills in using Hugging Face Transformers for sentiment analysis.
  • Learn how to integrate sentiment analysis into a chatbot application.

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 8

  • Step 1: Setting Up the Environment

    To begin working with Hugging Face Transformers, you need to set up your environment by installing the necessary libraries and tools.

    Open a new Google Colab Notebook. Don’t forget to change the runtime environment to use the T4 GPU as demonstrated in Quest 1, Step 5.

    Click on the “+ Code” and run the following command to install the required libraries:

    !pip install accelerate protobuf sentencepiece torch 
git+https://github.com/huggingface/transformers huggingface_hub
    Python

    Run the code block and wait for the installation to complete.

    Sample Output:

    Code Summary:

    • accelerate: Optimizes the performance of models.
    • protobuf: A serialization library used for data exchange.
    • sentencepiece: A tokenizer and detokenizer library.
    • torch: PyTorch, a popular machine learning framework.
    • transformers: The Hugging Face Transformers library.
    • huggingface_hub: Provides access to the Hugging Face model hub.

    This command installs several libraries that will allow you to use and optimize machine learning models from Huggingface. These libraries handle everything from loading models and tokenizing text to optimizing performance and accessing the Hugging Face model repository.

    Imagine you’re setting up a new kitchen. Before you can start cooking, you need to get all your utensils and ingredients ready. Similarly, in this step, you’re gathering all the tools and libraries you’ll need to work with advanced language models. These tools help you load the models, break down text into manageable pieces, and make sure everything runs smoothly on your computer.

  • Step 2: Loading the Pre-trained Language Model (Llama 2)

    From here on out, you can click on the “+ Code” button to add a new code cell and write the code from each step in it. After writing your code, hit the play button (triangle icon) to execute it. For adding descriptions or notes, use the “+ Text” button to create markdown cells. This will help you keep your notebook organized and easy to read.

    Next, you will learn how to load a pre-trained LLM from the Hugging Face model hub.

    Import the necessary libraries:

    from transformers import AutoModelForCausalLM, 
AutoTokenizer, pipeline
from huggingface_hub import login
import torch
    Python

    Log in to your Hugging Face account. You can refer to Quest 1 to get your access token.

    # Replace 'your-access-token' with your 
actual Hugging Face access token
login(token="your-access-token")
    Python

    You’ll need to log in to Hugging Face to access online resources, and load a pre-trained language model and its tokenizer. Logging in is needed if you want to access specific features or private models on Hugging Face, but it’s not necessary if you’re running the model locally.

    Load the pre-trained model and tokenizer:

    model_id = "NousResearch/Llama-2-7b-chat-hf"
model = AutoModelForCausalLM.from_pretrained(model_id, torch_dtype=torch.float16, device_map="auto")
tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_id)
tokenizer.use_default_system_prompt = False
    Python

    Write these codes in one block and press the play button to execute the code cell. The output should look similar to this:

    The model generates text based on input, while the tokenizer breaks down the text into tokens that the model can understand and process efficiently. The model and tokenizer work together to convert text into a format the model can process and then convert the model’s output back into readable text.

    Think of the model as a chef who can cook delicious meals (generate text), and the tokenizer as a kitchen assistant who prepares the ingredients (breaks down text into tokens) so the chef can work more efficiently. The assistant makes sure everything is ready for the chef to use, and after the chef is done, the assistant helps to present the dish beautifully (converts the output back into readable text). Logging in to Hugging Face is like getting access to a special recipe book that the chef can use, but it’s optional as you might already have the recipes you need (locally hosted).

    The use of torch_dtype=torch.float16 optimizes model performance by using 16-bit floating-point precision, and device_map="auto" ensures the model runs efficiently on either CPU or GPU.

    This is like giving the chef high-quality, pre-measured ingredients that are easier to cook with (optimizing performance), and device_map="auto" makes sure the chef has the best kitchen equipment available, whether it’s a regular stove (CPU) or a high-speed one (GPU).

    Code Summary:

    • AutoModelForCausalLM: Loads a pre-trained causal language model.
    • AutoTokenizer: Loads the tokenizer associated with the pre-trained model.
    • model_id: Specifies the identifier of the pre-trained model.
    • torch_dtype=torch.float16: Optimizes model performance by using 16-bit floating-point precision.
    • device_map="auto": Automatically selects the appropriate device (CPU or GPU) for model inference.
  • Step 3: Exploring Model Details

    Now that you have loaded the pre-trained model, you will explore some functions to output details about the model. Understanding these details will help you gain insights into the model’s architecture and capabilities.

    Get the model configuration. Add a new code block and write the following code:

    config = model.config 
#Retrieves the configuration of the loaded model, 
#which includes details such as the model architecture, 
#number of layers, hidden size, etc.

print(config)
    Python

    Run the code block and get and output similar to this:

    This output may seem overwhelming, but don’t worry. We’ll focus on the most relevant properties for this campaign to help you understand the model better.

    Model Name and Path:

    _name_or_path: “NousResearch/Llama-2-7b-chat-hf”

    This tells you the specific model you are using. It’s like knowing the name of the book you’re reading. In this case, it’s the “meta-llama/Llama-2-7b-chat-hf” model from Hugging Face.

    Hidden Size:

    hidden_size: 4096

    This indicates the size of the hidden layers in the model. Think of it as the brainpower of the model – a larger hidden size means the model can handle more complex patterns in the data.

    Number of Hidden Layers:

    num_hidden_layers: 32

    This tells you how many hidden layers the model has. More layers can enable the model to learn more complex features from the data. In this case, there are 32 layers.

    You can learn more about the other model properties as you progress through your journey in large-language models.

    Next, display the model architecture. Add a new code block and write the following code:

    #Outputs a summary of the model architecture, 
#showing the various layers and their configurations.
print(model)
    Python

    Run the code block and get and output similar to this:

    The print(model) function provides a detailed summary of the model’s architecture. To understand the components, imagine the model as a device that has this simple architecture: Input, Process, Output.

    Input (Embedding): Imagine you have a huge dictionary with 32,000 words. Each word is represented by a unique 4096-number code. This is like converting each word into a unique barcode.

    Process (Layers): The model processes these barcodes through 32 different steps (layers). At each step, it looks at the words and their contexts, refining its understanding of the input.

    Output (Generating Text): After processing, the model uses the refined information to decide which words to generate next, converting the barcodes back into readable words.

  • Step 4: Generating Text

    Try interacting with our model! Run the code below in a new code cell in your notebook:

    #This is the text input you provide to the model. 
#It’s like asking the model a question or giving it a starting
# sentence.
sample_prompt = "Hello, how are you?"

#The tokenizer converts your text into 
#tokens (numbers that represent words or sub-words). 
#This is necessary because the model works with numbers, 
#not raw text. The return_tensors="pt" part tells the t
#okenizer to return the tokens as a PyTorch tensor, 
#which is a data structure used in machine learning.
input_ids = tokenizer.encode(sample_prompt, return_tensors="pt")

#This line checks if you have a GPU available to speed up 
#the processing. Else, it will just use your CPU.
input_ids = input_ids.to('cuda' if torch.cuda.is_available() else 'cpu')

#The model generates a response based on your input tokens:
output = model.generate(input_ids, max_length=50, num_beams=5, no_repeat_ngram_size=2)
#max_length=50:The maximum length of the generated response 
#is 50 tokens. You can of course adjust this to get 
#longer responses.
#num_beams=5: This uses a technique called beam search 
#with 5 beams to generate better quality responses.
#no_repeat_ngram_size=2: This prevents the model
# from repeating the same phrase or sequence words. 
#The tokenizer converts the generated tokens back into human-readable text.

#Decode the output back to text
response = tokenizer.decode(output[0], skip_special_tokens=True)

#Finally, output the respnose
print(f"Generated Response: {response}")
    Python

    Sample Output:

    Code Summary:

    • tokenizer.encode(sample_prompt, return_tensors="pt"): Encodes the sample prompt into token IDs.
    • input_ids.to('cuda' if torch.cuda.is_available() else 'cpu'): Moves the input IDs to GPU if available.
    • model.generate(input_ids, max_length=50, num_beams=5, no_repeat_ngram_size=2): Generates a response using the model.
    • tokenizer.decode(output[0], skip_special_tokens=True): Decodes the model output into human-readable text.

    With the Llama 2 model now generating contextually relevant text, you've unlocked one of the many powerful capabilities of Large Language Models (LLMs). Text generation is just the start—these models can perform a variety of other tasks.

    In the next steps, you'll explore these tasks, demonstrating the versatility and real-world applications of LLMs.

  • Step 5: Named Entity Recognition (NER)

    Named Entity Recognition (NER) is a crucial task in NLP that involves identifying and categorizing entities within text. These entities can include names of people, organizations, locations, dates, and more. NER is commonly used in applications like information extraction, content classification, and even privacy-preserving tasks like data masking to protect sensitive information.

    In this step, you’ll implement NER using the Hugging Face Transformers library, leveraging the versatility of the Llama 2 model. The goal is to identify named entities in a given text and categorize them appropriately.

    Add a new Code Block and write the following code:

    from transformers import AutoModelForTokenClassification, AutoTokenizer, pipeline

# Load a pre-trained NER model
model_name = "dbmdz/bert-large-cased-finetuned-conll03-english"
tokenizer = AutoTokenizer.from_pretrained(model_name)
model = AutoModelForTokenClassification.from_pretrained(model_name)

# Create an NER pipeline
ner_pipeline = pipeline("ner", model=model, tokenizer=tokenizer)

# Test the NER pipeline with a sample sentence
test_sentence = "Apple is planning to build a new campus in Austin."
result = ner_pipeline(test_sentence)
print(result)
    Python

    This code initializes the NER pipeline with the pre-trained BERT model fine-tuned on the CoNLL-2003 dataset for NER tasks. It then runs a test input to extract named entities from the sentence.

    Run the code, and you should get an output similar to this:

    Pay attention to the last section of the output. There will be a list of detected entities in the text along with their labels and confidence scores.

    “Apple” is detected as “I-ORG” with a confidence level of “0.99”.

    Add a new code block and write the following function that will format the output to replace the detected entities in the original sentence:

    def display_masked_sentence(sentence, ner_results):
    masked_sentence = sentence
    for entity in ner_results:
        entity_word = entity['word']
        entity_label = entity['entity']
        masked_sentence = masked_sentence.replace(entity_word, f"[{entity_label}]")
    return masked_sentence

# Test the function with the NER results
masked_sentence = display_masked_sentence(test_sentence, result)
print(masked_sentence)
    Python

    This function takes the original sentence and the NER results as input. It loops through the detected entities and replaces each entity in the sentence with its corresponding label (e.g., [I-ORG], [I-LOC]).

    Run the code block and you should get an output similar to this:

    For the sentence “Apple is planning to build a new campus in Austin.”, with "Apple" recognized as an organization (I-ORG) and "Austin" as a location (I-LOC).

    Having successfully identified and masked entities in text, the next step will guide you through summarization. Summarization is a critical task in NLP, enabling the distillation of lengthy documents or articles into concise and coherent summaries.

  • Step 6: Summarization

    Summarization is a crucial task in NLP that involves condensing a lengthy piece of text into a shorter version while preserving its key points and overall meaning. This is particularly useful in scenarios where quick overviews of long documents are needed, such as news articles, research papers, or legal documents.

    In this step, you will implement a summarization pipeline using the Hugging Face Transformers library. The goal is to generate concise summaries from a given text, making it easier to digest large volumes of information efficiently.

    Add a new code block and write the following code:

    # Load the summarization pipeline
summarizer = pipeline("summarization", model="facebook/bart-large-cnn")

# Test the summarizer with a longer input text
long_text = (
    "The quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog. The lazy dog, however, was not really lazy. "
    "It was simply tired from chasing after the quick brown fox all day. The two animals had a "
    "long history of playful rivalry, with the fox always outwitting the dog. Despite their differences, "
    "they shared a bond of mutual respect and friendship."
)

summary = summarizer(long_text, max_length=50, min_length=25, do_sample=False)

print(summary[0]['summary_text'])
    Python

    Code Summary:

    • summarizer: This initializes the summarization pipeline using the pre-trained facebook/bart-large-cnn model, which is particularly effective for generating summaries of long documents.
    • long_text: A sample paragraph is used to test the summarization pipeline.
    • max_length and min_length: These parameters control the length of the generated summary, allowing you to specify a desired range of the summary's length.

    Run the code block and your output should be similar to this:

    This demonstrates the ability to distil a passage into its essential elements, which is valuable in many real-world applications, including content curation, news aggregation, and more.

    With summarization covered, the next step will explore another common NLP task: Question-Answering (QA). QA involves extracting precise answers to specific questions from a given context, a task highly relevant in building chatbots, virtual assistants, and information retrieval systems. The upcoming step will guide you through setting up a QA pipeline using Hugging Face Transformers and the Llama 2 model.

  • Step 7: Performing Question-Answering

    This step delves into QA, a fundamental task in natural language processing that involves extracting answers to questions from a given context. The process includes setting up a QA pipeline using Hugging Face Transformers and the pre-trained Llama 2 model.

    In this step, you'll set up a QA pipeline using the Hugging Face Transformers library. The aim is to provide a precise answer to a question based on the information provided in a text passage.

    Add a new Code Block and write the following code:

    # Load the QA pipeline
qa_pipeline = pipeline("question-answering", model="deepset/roberta-base-squad2")

# Define the context and the question
context = (
    "Apple Inc. is an American multinational technology company headquartered in Cupertino, California, "
    "that designs, develops, and sells consumer electronics, computer software, and online services. "
    "It is considered one of the Big Five companies in the U.S. information technology industry, along with "
    "Amazon, Google, Microsoft, and Facebook."
)
question = "Where is Apple Inc. headquartered?"

# Get the answer
answer = qa_pipeline(question=question, context=context)

print(f"Question: {question}")
print(f"Answer: {answer['answer']}")
    Python

    Running the code should yield something like:

    Code Summary:

    • qa_pipeline: This initializes the question-answering pipeline using the pre-trained deepset/roberta-base-squad2 model, which is fine-tuned on the SQuAD 2.0 dataset, a benchmark dataset for QA tasks.
    • context: A passage of text from which the model will extract the answer.
    • question: The specific question you want to be answered based on the context provided.
    • answer: The output will be the most relevant answer to the question, as determined by the model.

    This showcases the model's ability to understand a given context and extract specific information in response to a targeted question, making it highly useful for building interactive systems.
